  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "This assessment is designed to quickly gather critical information about the patient's condition, including the chief complaint, vital signs (such as temperature, blood pressure, heart rate, and respiratory rate), and a brief history of the present illness or injury.",
    "Triage categorization directly influences the allocation of resources 14, because triage is not a one-time assessment but a continuous process.",
    "Patients with the highest urgency levels are treated immediately and often directed to specialized areas within the ED equipped to handle severe cases (e.g., resuscitation rooms).",
    "Those with lower urgency levels may wait longer and be seen in order of priority based on their triage category 16.",
    "It is not excluded that patients' conditions can change, necessitating a reassessment and potential re-categorization of their urgency level 15."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
